  "text": "## Flink Windowing API Extension Points\n\nThe Apache Flink windowing API provides extension points through abstract base classes and interfaces that developers must implement to create custom window assigners and triggers.\n\n### 1. WindowAssigner (sg-evals/flink--0cc95fcc:flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/assigners/WindowAssigner.java)\n\nThe abstract base class `WindowAssigner<T, W extends Window>` is the primary extension point for implementing custom window assignment logic. Developers must implement the following abstract methods:\n\n- **`Collection<W> assignWindows(T element, long timestamp, WindowAssignerContext context)`** (line 53): Assigns zero or more windows to an incoming element based on its timestamp and current processing time. The context allows querying the current processing time.\n\n- **`Trigger<T, W> getDefaultTrigger()`** (line 65): Returns the default trigger associated with this window assigner. Every window assigner must provide a trigger that determines when window results should be emitted.\n\n- **`TypeSerializer<W> getWindowSerializer(ExecutionConfig executionConfig)`** (line 71): Returns a TypeSerializer for the window type produced by this assigner, enabling proper serialization of window metadata.\n\n- **`boolean isEventTime()`** (line 77): Indicates whether windows are assigned based on event-time (true) or processing-time (false). This determines how the runtime handles watermarks and timers.\n\nAdditionally, the class defines a nested `WindowAssignerContext` interface (line 88) that provides a `getCurrentProcessingTime()` method for the assigner to query system time during window assignment.\n\n### 2. MergingWindowAssigner (sg-evals/flink--0cc95fcc:flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/assigners/MergingWindowAssigner.java)\n\nThe `MergingWindowAssigner<T, W extends Window>` extends `WindowAssigner` and is used for window types that can overlap and merge (such as session windows). It adds one critical abstract method:\n\n- **`void mergeWindows(Collection<W> windows, MergeCallback<W> callback)`** (line 42): Determines which windows (if any) should be merged. When windows need to be merged, the implementation invokes the callback's `merge(Collection<W> toBeMerged, W mergeResult)` method to signal the merge operation.\n\nThe class also defines the `MergeCallback<W>` interface (line 49-57) with a single method: `void merge(Collection<W> toBeMerged, W mergeResult)` that implementers call to specify which windows should be merged and what the resulting window should be.\n\n### 3. Trigger (sg-evals/flink--0cc95fcc:flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/triggers/Trigger.java)\n\nThe abstract base class `Trigger<T, W extends Window>` defines the lifecycle methods for window evaluation. Developers must implement these abstract methods:\n\n- **`TriggerResult onElement(T element, long timestamp, W window, TriggerContext ctx)`** (line 67): Called for every element added to a pane. The trigger determines whether the pane should fire and produce results.\n\n- **`TriggerResult onProcessingTime(long time, W window, TriggerContext ctx)`** (line 77): Called when a processing-time timer (registered via TriggerContext) fires. Enables triggers to react to system clock progression.\n\n- **`TriggerResult onEventTime(long time, W window, TriggerContext ctx)`** (line 87): Called when an event-time timer fires (when watermarks pass a registered time). Enables event-time based trigger logic.\n\n- **`void clear(W window, TriggerContext ctx)`** (line 118): Called when a window is being purged. Implementers must clean up any state and delete registered timers.\n\nAdditionally, there are non-abstract methods:\n\n- **`boolean canMerge()`** (line 97): Returns false by default. Subclasses that support merging should override this to return true.\n\n- **`void onMerge(W window, OnMergeContext ctx)`** (line 108): Called when windows merge. The default implementation throws UnsupportedOperationException; merging triggers must override this.\n\nThe Trigger class also defines two context interfaces:\n- **`TriggerContext`** (line 126): Provides methods to register/delete timers, get processing time/watermark, and access partitioned state.\n- **`OnMergeContext`** (line 189): Extends TriggerContext and adds `mergePartitionedState()` for merging trigger state across merged windows.\n\n### 4. EventTimeSessionWindows (sg-evals/flink--0cc95fcc:flink-streaming-java/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/assigners/EventTimeSessionWindows.java)\n\nThis concrete reference implementation extends `MergingWindowAssigner<Object, TimeWindow>` and demonstrates how to implement a session-based window assigner:\n\n- **`Collection<TimeWindow> assignWindows(Object element, long timestamp, WindowAssignerContext context)`** (line 61-63): Creates a single TimeWindow spanning from the element's timestamp to `timestamp + sessionTimeout`. Each new element starts a new session that can later merge with others if gaps are bridged.\n\n- **`void mergeWindows(Collection<TimeWindow> windows, MergeCallback<TimeWindow> c)`** (line 113-115): Delegates to the static utility method `TimeWindow.mergeWindows()`, which handles the logic of identifying overlapping windows and merging them into larger contiguous time windows.\n\nThe implementation also provides:\n- `getDefaultTrigger()`: Returns an EventTimeTrigger to fire windows when event-time advances via watermarks\n- `getWindowSerializer()`: Returns a TimeWindow.Serializer for proper window serialization\n- `isEventTime()`: Returns true since session windows are based on element timestamps (event-time)\n\nThe class supports both static gap creation via `withGap(Duration)` (line 83) and dynamic gaps via `withDynamicGap()` (line 96) for extracting session timeouts from elements.\n\n### 5. TimeWindow (sg-evals/flink--0cc95fcc:flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/windows/TimeWindow.java)\n\nThe `TimeWindow` class (extending `Window`) represents a time-based window interval from start (inclusive) to end (exclusive). Key characteristics:\n\n- **Constructor**: `TimeWindow(long start, long end)` (line 50): Creates a window representing the time interval [start, end).\n\n- **Key accessor methods**:\n  - `getStart()` (line 61): Returns the inclusive start timestamp\n  - `getEnd()` (line 71): Returns the exclusive end timestamp\n  - `maxTimestamp()` (line 84): Returns `end - 1`, the largest timestamp in the window\n\n- **Merge utility methods**:\n  - `intersects(TimeWindow other)` (line 116): Checks if windows overlap or are adjacent\n  - `cover(TimeWindow other)` (line 121): Creates the minimal window covering both windows\n  - **`static void mergeWindows(Collection<TimeWindow> windows, MergeCallback<TimeWindow> c)`** (line 208-254): Sorts windows by start time and merges overlapping windows, invoking the callback for each merge group. This is the utility method used by EventTimeSessionWindows and other merging assigners.\n\n- **Serialization**: Includes a nested `Serializer` class (line 130) and `TimeWindowSerializerSnapshot` (line 191) for type evolution support.\n\n## Summary\n\nThe extension points form a chain: WindowAssigner implementations define `assignWindows()` to produce Window instances, specify a Trigger via `getDefaultTrigger()`, and declare whether they support merging (MergingWindowAssigner). Trigger implementations react to element arrivals and timer fires via `onElement()`, `onEventTime()`, and `onProcessingTime()`. For merging scenarios (e.g., session windows), both the assigner implements `mergeWindows()` and the trigger implements `onMerge()` to coordinate window and state consolidation. TimeWindow is the concrete window type produced by most time-based assigners and provides merge utility logic.\n"
}

